tiers of a continuing sectarian order. Hiba Bou Akar argues these neighborhoods are arranged, not in the expectation of a bright future, but according to the logic of "the war yet to come": urban planning plays on fears and differences, rumors of war, and paramilitary strategies to organize everyday life. As she shows, war in times of peace is not fought with tanks, artillery, and rifles, but involves a more mundane territorial contest for land and apartment sales, zoning and planning regulations, and infrastructure projects.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCity planningxPolitical aspectszLebanonzBeirut. 0aCity planningzLebanonzBeirut. 0aCommunalismzLebanonzBeirut. 4aBeirut. 4aMiddle East. 4afrontiers. 4amilitarization. 4aplanning. 4apost-conflict. 4areligious-political organizations. 4asectarianism. 4aurbanism. 4awar. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360561940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503605619423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503605619.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles